dive.notes:
First club dive!
Kit: Apeks regs, one cylinder of own, one borrowed. Club drysuit, scubapro fleece undersuit, borrowed weight harness, borrowed computer, own Scubapro fins, 32kg weight.
Dive: Good visibility, saw crabs, a sea spider and loads of starfish.
Slightly sticky inflation valve caused me to over inflate suit and shoot to surface, which spooked me and spoiled my confidence for dive, so finger tipped the rest.
Top notch roll sausage from Harvey on Surface Interval

Second club dive. No change to equipment from dive #1 I was much calmer and able to take more in - saw a lot of crabs. Did not attempt to work on bouyancy after first fright, just enjoyed the dive finger-tipping along.

Weekend staying in mum dads caravan in Argyle Caravan park with Isla.Kit: As previous but new SPG with depth guage. Added 3kg clip weights to get down. Rolled off rib into water. Completed mask clearing and air sharing skills. Observed loads of crabs and starfish. Wet from shoulder down though.
Kit: Added 1Kg shot pouch. Walk in from slip way with long bimble - good controlled breathing and enjoyable dive.

Dive Organiser: Thomas Duff Kit Setup: as per previous dive Species Encountered:Crabs, Squat Lobsters Skills Completed or Practiced: None Kit Repair Notes: nothing to repair. Feet still feeling floaty so may want to try additional ankle weights. General Notes: Bouyancy improving. Enjoyed dive and swim in. Learnings: Don't wave to observers: waved to Isla who was on shore and made it look like I was in distress. Took rob from Caravan Park slipway round to Kenmore point. Moored boat and walked in. Thomas then took us to a wall with a steep drop off down to 20m The drop off initially making me very nervous, casuing me to really go through my air. No skills done as terrain not suitable, just an experience dive. Observed crabs fighting over scraps of meat. Began to feel very cold, but we were ascending by this time anyway.

Dive Organiser: Thomas Duff Dive Purpose: Fun dive - last dive of weekend at Argyle Caravan par. Dive risk plan notes: n/a Kit Setup: No change from previous dive Species Encountered: Crabs, Lobsters Activities Observed:n/a Skills Completed or Practiced: n/a Kit Repair Notes: feet still floating up - more ankle weights? General Notes: Improved bouyancy - was going really well for ~1/2 the dive. Bit of a long swim in as well overshit the slipway coming back up. Learnings: Dont wave to observers - was waving to Isla, which looked like distress signal to shore cover.

Dive Organiser: Thomas Duff Dive Purpose: Training weekend - Kerr Thomas did all weekend, Alan Kimberley did one day, Dive risk plan notes: n/a Kit Setup: As per previous dive, but borrowed a weightbelt. Had difficulty getting kit set up as hoses were wrong on regs. Species Encountered: Cod. Activities Observed: None Skills Completed or Practiced: Attempted a Kit Repair Notes: Stick to a weight harness in future. Notes: Dive plan changed from diving from Conger Alley to Finnart instead, due to Air Ambulance being needed at Arrochar and closing the road. Result was we were hurried stressed gong in to the water. I couldn't get myself neutrally bouyant at all. I then failed my 10m ascent as I was finning constantly and tired myself out. My weight belt then began slipped - aborted dive and managed to get belt up to the shallows where Thomas could recover it. Learnings: Get bouyancy nailed before doing ascent. Dont borrow kit, don't be pressured into hurrying into the water.

Dive Organiser: Thomas Duff Dive Purpose:Training weekend - Kerr Thomas did all weekend, Alan Kimberley did one day, Dive risk plan notes: n/a Kit Setup: As per previous dive Species Encountered: none noted Activities Observed: none noted Skills Completed or Practiced: 10metre Sports Diver ascent completes Kit Repair Notes: Stick to harness, sort out drysuit hoses. General Notes:Much better second dive, with ascent on SMB being successfull Learnings: Overweighted as losing air from neck rapidly whenever I approached neutral bouyancy.

New suit so played safe with 20Kg weight Camped at Resipole Camp site on friday night in prep for days diving on saturday. Bimbled about in 4 (Thomas Duff, Theresa Campbell and Russell Leitch) Saw loads of scallops and large crabs. Got used to suit fairly quicjly - got bouyancy and could fin pivot at 6m fairly easily. We came out a litt off the bay at some lovely white rocks.

Dropped weight by 1Kg Completed 10m ascent fairly easily though Iw as losing a fair bit of air at my neck - had to maintain bouyancy by topping up and occassionally finning - expensive in air consumption! Came back down. Managed to stay calm in zero viz while Theresa did her first ascent attempt. Buddied off with Russell, leaving Thomas and Theresa to re-attempt in clearer water. Enjoyed dive with Russell, mostly matched my bouyancy to Russell despite being overweighted I think. Russell put up SMB and we did safety stops on way up. Just about to surface when SMB pulled up by Alan N.

Skills completed - big step / jump entry and shared air swim. Saw an eel and a Lion Man Jellyfish Bouyancy poor to begin with but got better as dive progressed. Definitely felt overweighted. Dive computer had much shorter safety stop than inidcated on Thomas's

Fun dive with Thomas Bouyancy started well but lost it after a while - felt very unstable and still losing air at neck when otherwise neutrally bouyant. Need to weigh my harness ahead of next dive to see where I am.

Advanced Open Water first training dive with Kathy.
11kg weight and completed peak performance bouyancy etc
Spotted a Stingray moing through at 30ish metres below us.

Another Advanced Open Water training dive - Deep dive this time, through the blue hole with Kimberley from below, holding above waiting on other pair of trainees coming through.
Fun dive, loads of shoals of fish.

Boat dive to Waikiki wall. Roll off boat and down rope line to start of harbour wall.
Usual lvely viz and lots of life including octopus and trumpet fish.

Another boat dive where we visited three wrecks just off the harbour wall, so boat was only really just taking us around the corner from the harbour to the other side of the main storm wall to where 6 boats have all sunk in the vicinity of the harbour.
Although a boat dive, it was a free descent and ascent as we were fallowing the back of the harbour wall.
First boat had lobsters sat on the wreckage.
Second boat allowed a swimthrough, where there was lot and lots of life hiding in all the corners of the boat and third was a larger ship that we swam past.
Brilliant dive and Kimberley really got her confidence on the ascents.

PADI AOW
Jump entry dive off the high pier at Playa Chica near the main diving area.
Great fun stepping off and dropping a good 6 meters to the water. finned out on the surace to the divers ring and descended from there.
Swam round and did the blue hole again, reverse from earlier dive before coming back to near the diving ring to a flat sandy area where we did our navigation skills at 11m

Another great dive out from Playa Chica, practicing bouyancy and navigation skills.
Loads of starfish, a pufferfish and an Angel Shark to see. Brilliant really enoyable dive.

ANother dive from Playa Chica, this tiem with Hugo from Tech Diving.
Very good dive, bit of current coming back in to the beach.
Another lovely octopus to see down at the ropes.

Another good dive - jump entry from pier due to tide.
Loads of starfish to see and saw some huge tuna swimming through the area.
Again, some current to deal with but not terrible.

Boat Dive from Playa Blanca harbour arranged via Techno Diving with a decent sized RIB.
Lovely calm sea and had a brilliant dive with no current to worry about and could happily explore the live in and around the volcanic rock.
Very calm, relaxed dive.

Great dive, loads to see, lots of Barracuda cruising through the museum.
Wasn't overly impressed with the museum itself but it does attract interesting life.

First ever night dive - in in twilight out in the dark. Moved along rapidly with tide, coming in on a very gradual ascent. Not a great deal to see - a dog fish and some prawns. Kerr kicked face a few times

Cold still october morning. Went in with 17Kg (12 in harness, 4 on BCD and 1 on ankles First dive I've experienced go dark, I think due to run off mixing with salt causing light to refract. Bouyancy still not great - still losing air at neck and feeling overweighted. Passed a skate, eel and a good variety of fish (pretty red fish with black bars) Loads of small fish and critters going about that only saw when stopped for safety stop

Dropped weight to 16Kg - could still drop down no problem with full breath. Bouyancy much better than first dive bu still very inflated at neutral bouyancy. Saw a curled up dogfish and some big cod / pollock.

Dive was supposed to be at St Catherine's pier but Air Ambulance had closed road so ended up at A Frames. Afternoon dive bimbling up and down and got 2 skills done: mask clearing and 50m blind swim. Nt much wildlife to see. Came back in swept along in strong current.
Had added a thermal base layer under Scubapro suit. 12Kg in harness, 2Kg in BCD and 1Kg on feet.

dive.buddy: Kerr Hamilton, Gary Walinck, Thomas Duff
dive.notes: Kerr's sport diver rescue - I was playing the victim. Quick bimble along (Told off by Thomas for going along too quckly). Kerr got rescue signed off but struggled controlling my ascent. Need to review my harness/BCD config to improve accessibility
Kerr leading for fun dive. Passed through a couple of shoals of fish. Kerr did 3 nice strafes of the reef on a slow ascent and a one mnute safety stop at 3 metres.

First dive with "fixed" cuff on drysuit and new undersuit and it caused problems getting descent started. 6Kg (!!) added to get me to drop. Initially paired with Jamie but had to swap with Jamie after Craig Campbell came close to an uncontrolled ascent. Good dive generally - only life to see was a stafish spawning ground. On surface practiced my rescue. Didn't make a 2nd dive as wasn't feeling great after toilet break. Cath W provided cracking soup.

Diving with Craig - my first attempt to lead dive. Bad start as computer switched off at 5 metres. Continued on just using console depth gauge and Craig's computer. Intended to zigzage back up reef but this was difficult without own computer so took one long sweep. At 3m Craig's fet went bouyant. Tried a couple of times to right him but was concerned he was anxious and starting to panic, so just ascended form where we were. Still feeling overweighted!

Second dive lead - compuer working again. Followed same path as first five, nice calm bimble, this time finding lobsters and fish to look at.ried to zigzag up reef but found judging distance travelled difficult and ended up further up the loch than intended when we surfaced.

Went in to left side of the castle. Aim was to navigate around the castle and exit to the right. No problems generally but did accidentally drop below 15m briefly. Tried to follow a 70 degree then 160 degree heading, then out on 250. Not sure when I went wrong exactly but found I was travelling along but not ascending so realised I must be well off and heading along a sandbar. rather than risk going further awry, put SMB up and ascended. Theresa did well sorting a minor tangle for me. 1min 3m safety stop on way up and surfaced safely a good way out. Gentle fin back in to beach without incident.
Reverse of dive 32 with Theresa. Again, I led and navigated. Visibility was very poor to the point of not enjoying the dive. Navigation was spot on though and we surfaced right at the flag.

Dive Organiser: Jenny Young Dive organized by Jenny with Thomas for James Nimmo's BI Assessment. Dove as a 4, buddied with James Nimmo, Thomas Duff and Jenny Young observing.
I was assessed on mask clearing (SDO1) and Compass work (SDO2) both of which signed off by Thomas on the day.
Mask clearing went fine - partial flood at 3m to get used to the cold water and full mask removal x2 at 10m.
Compass bearing went OK, came back to our point of reference really well.
Learnings: - Be careful reading out bearings - I made my usual mistake of getting it 180 degrees out! Could cause someone to get lost. - When I came back to the compass bearing reference, which was an unattached bouy mooring, I swam under the big arched hoop of rope - slight snag risk which wasn't necessary to the dive, should have gone around - Got too far from buddy on surface swim
Wins: - Did the dive without ankle weights and didn't freak out feeling air going to feet.
Dive was comfortable, bouyancy wasn't brilliant, went up a couple of meters at times, from about 18 minutes onwards - possibly still overweighted, so holding too much air making ascent in the shallow needing a bit more proactive air dumping. Discussed with other divers - new drysuit on order and next dives in fresh water, so maybe drop a kilo, but not worth doing full weight checks until i'm in new drysuit.
New o'three gloves are comfortable but the wrist straps are awkward with watch and compass

Dive Organiser: Jenny Young Dive organized by Jenny with Thomas for James Nimmo's BI Assessment. Dove as a 4, I buddied with James Nimmo, with Thomas Duff and Jenny Young observing.
This dive was to assess James' rescue ascent. Rescue went OK albeit slowly with James struggling to start ascent (dumping too much air once lift started - again sign of over-weighting on me).
Once up, Jamie towed me in successfully. We regrouped at the end of the pier and agreed to have another short dive, going around the pier and coming up in to the bay on the westerly side of the slip.
On this bimble I had reasonably good bouyancy and enjoyed examining some metal struxtures that I'll need to find out more about.
Learnings: - On initial descent, after my initial I must have drifted over Jenny and came down right on top of her - need to watch my landing point better. - Again, drifted too far from James on surface - stay closer!

Weather: Sunny Sea: Calm Visibility: 20m Temp: 14?
On holiday with family for a short week in Lloret De Mar - didn't want to lose whole day, so a shore dive with Dolphin Dive Centre from the nearby beach was just perfect. Got log book and tickets checked and sized up for gear on the Monday when we stopped in to book and when I arrived at 8am on the Wednesday, we just had to load up the gear onto trailer pulled by a trail bike, put on the wet suit and jump in the van down to the beach and got kitted up with Eva.
April in the Balearic sea in a wetsuit is COLD
Lovely dive over the golden sands - lots of different varieties of colourful and bright silver fish and spotted a couple of lovely little nudibranches.
As we were diving off a tourist beach, we both, unbeknown to each other, were actually collecting loads of bits of plastic and fishermens lead and line.
Good fun, if slightly cold.

Diving with Gary Walinck, Pam Morley and Lauren Ramage, Buddied with Lauren. First dive in new Otter tri-lam suit. Just used Harness weight and felt overweighted. Ended up swapping buddies early on as Gary had gone to assist Lauren with something - I stayed close to Pamela but lost sight of Gary & Lauren. Dive brief had allowed for scenario so we were happy to continue on just staying to 15m Some very interesting life at east end of reef including squat lobsters. Eventually re-united with Gary and Lauren before surfacing. Surfacing was challenging as Pamela's fin had become loose, and she began an uncontrolled ascent but both managed to stay calm and got out the water without incident.
Attempted dive lead and carried out SMB skill practice. Again, seperated in poor visibility and ended up paired with Lauren and completed the dive as a pair, and Pam did her dive with Gary.

First dive at Capernwray. Shore entry, swam around past lord lucan and did a shared ascent with Kerr for Sport Diver training. Came back down and continued dive.
Safe to say my introduction to Capernwray was not a good one - first attempt cancelled due to snow, a day late for this re-scheduled trip due to work being done on van and being in London with work and when I arrived in Lancaster on the Saturday night I found my room had been given away so ended sharing a room with Kerr and Alan.

Jump entry from pier. Bimble about finding landmarks. Went through aeroplane and came around. Just after leaving plane, Kerr and Alan's path diverged in very poor vis. I was closer to Kerr so immediately caught up with Kerr and signalled that we lost Alan. We spent 1 minute back to back trying to see Alan, then did a controlled ascent with safety spot and found Alan at surface. As we hadn't been down long we agreed to finish dive.

During surface interval met with a Divemaster from a local club who was looking for a buddy for a last dive. Given the excitement in previous dive I thought this was a good excuse to not have to tackle another ascent. Shore entry and Alan led for a good paced bimble right around the quarry. Quite hard going and legs were tired by the end. Topped up the divemasters car who was critically low on oil and made my way home.

Saturday morning dive trip with Russell to get back in the water after a bit of layoff. Nice early start got us at finnart for about 8am and in the water for 8.20 Arrived at Finnart first but heard it was to be a busy day with Glasgow Uni SAC arriving shortly after us for a training day. There has been a floating pontoon installed between the steps and the edge of the water - did make a nice platform to enter the water from but would make getting out more difficult. Forgot batteries for dive torch - big thanks to Russell's spare for saving the day - won't do that again. Dive itself was great - entered from pontoon and went out on ~330 bearing until we passed the third large beam, turned whttps://twitter.com/ScotlandDXesterley to head towards oil terminal at 15m (briefly dropping to 16.2m due to following wildlife), turned and came back long the reef until we came to the mess of cables where we headed back to our entry point and came up on Russell's SMB - was very happy with my ascent First life we saw were a number of moon jellyfish, which had a beautiful blue pulsing light going through them when a torch was shone on them. Sea bed had a lot of life with loads of squat lobsters, crabs as well as some small cod swimming about. Just before we ascended saw what looked like a huge crab tucked away under a rock.
2nd dive of the day with Russell. Same dive plan as first dive. Tide had come in so didn't see just as much life but still a very nice bimble just enjoying being in the water

Training dive at Prestonfield Quary, Inverkeithing. Overweighted with a 2Kg block over usual harness. We descended, Kath had an issue with mask and weights - I sank like a rock and struggled to get back up. Dove with Kath and Gordon - went around the quarry anti-clockwise, saw the cars and the speedboat - nice perch was hiding in the speedboad.
Successfully put up DSMB and got skill signed. Went up fine to about 6m and lost control a bit - realised had forgot to vent BCD after adding some to ascend at start of dive.
Really enjoyable dive all in all.

one-on-one dive with Donald who had just become BDO. Dive followed plan perfectly - headed out at right angles to shore. On way down think I saw a conger eel under alone rock shortly before heading west along to the reef.
Zigzagged along the reef - two big lovely wrass were out and about watching their territory and lost of small cod and other fish.
Sadly no more eels.
Safety stops went well and easy shore exit.

Removed 1Kg from set up prior to entering water.
Finned out to ~3m and tried to descend - Could submerge but was unable to drop right down. Donald came back up and gave me a 1Kg pouch.
Still couldn't drop - eventually managed to descend by finning a little downward.
Tried to get myself comfortable - legs felt light and felt off balance - suspected air trapped in suit so decended to a flat clear spot at 8m to try wriggling to see if I could loosen anything.
No joy displacing any air and suit felt tight came back up to 6m and did not feel right, didn't feel like I could make myself descend properly and legs still very light. Signalled to Donald to end dive and began ascent. Did safety stops properly at 6m and 3m, though at 3m safety Donald was having to assist, mainly because I was finning to keep my legs down, thus adding to bouyancy.
Surfaced safely and exited water.
Checked over kit immediately on shore and nothing obvious. Went right up andd dekitted at car. Only when dekitted and weight harness removed did we realise I had actually lost a 7Kg weight pouch from my harness, presumably when putting fins on.
Went back down to shore - 3 snorkerers were in water and one very kindly managed to recover my weight pouch intact in the shallows - definitely owe that man a beer!

*George Martin's first open water dive* Wednesday night training dive - drobe up with Jamie. Forgot fins - problems with borrowed find on big step - evetually resolved using Anne-Marie's fins.
Went in on 16Kg - could descend no problem. Had issues equalising ears on way down. As soon as I managed to get down, attempted rescue on Jamie, observed by Gordon.
Didn't vent Jamie's suit or keep his arm up, so ended up with runaway ascent. Also, I need to read computer more carefully - I keep reading max depth as current depth when ascending.
After re-descending had a nice bimble about with Jamie. Shoals of perch going about, maybe a couple of dozen perch, and some really large perch.
Saw what looked like very young pike going about in the weed.

Sunday dive trip to Twin Piers with Russell, Donald and Fraser who came along and kindly did shore cover.
First dive began with another 10m rescue attempt, with Russell as victim. Rescue was successful - far more controlled that previous dive at Prestonfield - and managed to get Russell up safely after a slight false start after dumping too much as we began ascending.

Fun dive, with myself acting as dive lead. Went down to 10m and turned along to find the reef then zigzagged back. Pleasant dive with plenty of life. Bouyancy wasn't great, I think due to thinking more about leading the dive.

PADI Dive with Diver's Cove from Sagres Harbour. 1hr drive from resort to Sagres, passing Storks and I think the Zoo I visited years ago. Travelled with Dutch Erik and a german gentlemen. Pre-dive brief agreed to buddy with Kimberley with us immediatelly following dive lead and other pair following us. Tricky start as Kimberley was underweighted and had sore ears but some time and an extra 2Kg got that sorted out. Nice gentle circle around harbour are, taking in the man-made harbour wall and cliff edge. Lots of sea slugs, a couple of nudibranches some fish and a well camoflaged Octopus to be seen. Prior to surfacing we came across two lobsters pots with octopus caught that the dive lead tried to free - only managed to free the second, the first refused to leave. Upon surfacing, a couple of people managed to get aboard boat before it lost it's anchor, so we had to spend 10-15 minutes chasing the boat prior to getting aboard.

PADI Dive with Diver's Cove from Sagres Harbour. 2nd dive of the day from Sagres Harbour. Concern about Kimberley's ears but she did well getting down to depth slowly. Dive started well, so some nice wrass and other fish as we bimbled into the caves. Caves themselves were a little disappointing - cloudy day meant the lighting in the caves was poor and the effect was lost. As we exited the first cave we got a taste of things to come as a current pulled us out and the wall separating the caves, into the next cave.
Once in the second cave, a "sloshing" motion current started, pulling us back and forth inside the cave, initially just a gentle push and pull but as we progressed through the cave it became stronger and stronger to the point we were being thrown around and I hit and was drawn along once side close to the ceiling, losing my reg and cutting my hand - by this point I was worried about seriously damaging equipment or being knocked out. Kimberley also got pushed downwards hard, causing pain in her ears, so we linked up with dive lead and made a swim for it and got out and surfaced as quickly as possible, no safety stop.
Some confusion on the surface as Erik, possibly a little in shock, could not locate his buddy, who was much nearer the boat. We'd surfaced quite far from boat, so dive lead and myself too turns towing Kimberley in. Dive lead said he'd never experienced anything like it at that site and later research backs this up, http://divescover.com/dive-site/shadow-canyon-ponta-dos-caminhos-/41328 rating the site as easy with no currents.
Learnings: - Don't have blind faith in dive lead, should have been trying to get low under the current much earlier - I shouldn't have let us come up without safety stop: there was no reason we couldn't have got further from the cliff wall and done at least a 1 minute safety. - Need to see if dive computer can be made louder - I was unaware of the SLOWS being given.

First dive on new 15l tank. Went with my thinner Scubapro undersuit and 17Kg of weight. took Dive lead on the dive (#2 logged) Straightforward walk in entry and went out heading over towards buiding on far side of loch then turned left at 15m to find reef.
Bimbled over reef without seeing a great deal when Gordon gave signal that he was out of air. Looking back I was pleased with reaction - took care retrieving and passing over octo to avoid tangles or fumbles. Donor ascent completed with reasonably good profle
After that we continues along and up the reef when Gordon again indicated out of air, but myself. Again, calmly removed reg and accepted gordons nd did a reasonable ascent. Again, dive profile looks reasonably good - maybe need to practice slowing them down a little.
By the time we finsihed the 2nd ascent and surfaced, we found the current had carried us quite a bit down the loch and out, with a reasonable swim in required.
Delighted to get a couple of dive lead dives done and last open water skills signed off for Sports Diver.

Great fun second dive. Again shore entry but turned right at 15m to look for small reef. Couldn't find it so doubled back to find big reef.
Followed a sole for a while before coming across a big Octopus who was looking in wonderful help. He watched us watching him for a couple of minutes before swimming in .
After that we found the large crab I thought I saw on the previous deve, I spotted a Conger hiding nd aw loads of pollock glinting in the light.
Surfaced, did a quick weight check which showed on my 12l with the Scubapro undersuit, I'm fine with 16Kg
Really fun dive.

This trip was initially cancelled due to bad weather forecast that never materialised, so Gordon Laing and I, with Tracey & Sam for shore cover, managed to make our way to the quarry after work to get my final skill, SDO4, signed off and my last dive lead.
Led the dive from a shore entry. Navigated the perimeter of ther quarry and headed round to the flat area at the north of the quarry where we carried out the assisted ascent.
First attempt I ascended too quickly and lost control of the lift somewhat. Corrected it before surfacing and we tried again and did in far more calmly and controlled.
After that it was a bimble in and headed home.

Afternoon dive after Eyemouth trip was cancelled. Van share up with Jamie Buddied with Donald.
Visibility was suprisingly good, good dive - nice view of some small fish as well as a huge Lobster
No incidents of note and no big learning points.

Second dive of the day.
Dropped down to 23/24m to try and find the furthest most frame. Found the area quite crowded with divers so came back up to ~15 minutes and came across the reef there.
Again, good vis, some nice wildlife including spotting a huge Conger Eels hiding, just popping his head out from the frame.

Early dive with Donald, Jamie and Colin. Really bad viz - snottery looking plankton everywhere and we nearly ran into a Jellyfish as we started to descend.
Decent enough dive apart from Mask flooding constantly

As per dive 46 but found big conger and big obster hiding under rocks near one another. Wasn't keen on the conger as he had perfect strike position on me so kept my distance.
Beautiful shoal of pollock congregating above the big vertical rock towards top of reef.

Carrick Castle trip expedition with club - 11 divers in total
Nice calm dive with Colin who did well with bouyancy.
I was dive lead and was navigating - plan was enter from toilet side of cast, 10 minutes out towards bouy, turn left 10 minutes, along ~15 minutes and turn left and in - add in safety stops we'd be about the 40 minute mark.
Plan went reasonably well, but unbeknown to me, flooding tide was putting more of a run on than I'd realised and 10 minutes bimbling along had carried us well beyond the castle. Found after a good few minutes when supposedly heading in that we had started getting deeper.
I got anxious and started to really doubt my compass bearings. At this point put SMB up and did an ascent - we didnt manage to hold it and ended up descending and ascending again and held it as long as we could before surfacing.
LOOOONG swim in followed
Learning - write my bearings down on wrist slate when navigating so I have something for reassurance.

Reverse of previous dive.
Wrote up bearings on wrist slate and apart from coming in a little early and catching the edge of the pier, naied the navigation.
Good dive - felt I led Colin well and kept him calm, including keeping him out the road of a massive Lions Mane jellyfish.
Passed Kimberley on way in to shore who was heading out with Gordon.

Expedition to Ballachulish slates organised by myself with the intention of getting a 30m+ dive for myself and Lauren Ramage before we went to Mull for similarly deep dives.
Carried out as planned - AlanB headed out, through the slight natural passageway to the right of the slate wall, down to depth and the headed east alomng the loch, gradually coming up the seabed till we hit the reefs - swam out, found the two anchors and headed right back, gently rising and degassing - we got back to the slate wall with plenty air and planned time so we went round the peninsula, had a look around the slate wall for a bit and back to the shore, running my air down to 50 bar

dive.tags: MD4, Master Diver, Swim without Mask
dive.notes:
Second dive - followed very similar route to dive 48, but not going down as deep.
Took opportunity while we had shore cover and out with Alan to do MD4 skill - did this without any real problem - felt like Alan was leading me round in circles but in fact we'd taken a straight line along the reef. Spend the rest of the dive having a fruitless hunt for clams - plenty of small ones but nothing of decent size.

Weather: Sunny Sea: Calm Visibility: 8m Temp: 12
First ever wreck dive - Sound of Mull with Ronnie, Fiona & Niamh Watson, James Nimmo, Alan Bews, Thomas Duff and Lauren Ramage.
Not as dark as I'd expected - loads of fish living in and around the wreck, one wrasse followed the divers about closely, presumably awaiting food stirred up.
Ronnie got me a piece of coal from the engine room.

Weather: Sunny Sea: Calm Visibility: 8m Temp: 12
2nd site of the day was the Thesis. Only really the hull remains, meaning you could go go in and out of sections as the hull plates are on the sea bed. Some huge pollock live in and around the hull.
Prior to the dive we were taken round some of the inaccessible rocks on the coast of Mull where was saw young seals and there mum and skipper also managed to feed two Eagles who swooped in from the coast to collect fish he'd thrown in.

Weather: Sunny Sea: Calm Visibility: 8m Temp: 12
Hugely impressive wreck absolutely covered in life, colourful coral everywhere. Did my first swimthrough of a reasonably small doorway under Ronnie's careful watch.

Weather: Rainy Sea: Choppy Visibility: 8m Temp: 12
Due to conditions, skipper decided to come into some sheltered bays for todays dives.
20 Metre Ascent?

First die at Craggen for myself, Russell Leitch, Harvey Williamson and Lauren Ramage. Quiet training dive,
Dive plan was for Russell and Harvey to go to 30+ metres and come back then regroup and Harvey and I do 20m Shared and from 6m Lauren to do mask removal swim.
Dive itself wasn't great: very rocky, slippery entry point made getting in difficult. I got in and promptly dropped my dive mask in ~1m of pea-soup water.
Started dive with Harveys mask and upon descent found equalising my ears harder then usual - from 5 metres I had to come back up slightly to equalise and keep pressure on my nose to keep equalising.
Vis was terrible - not the worst I've seen but quite disorientating and I found I had difficulty reading my compass with Harveys mask which was fogging.
After hitting the 33 mark we starting coming back, still looking for any signs of a reef or life in generaly but no sign. Harvey and Lauren then did 20m shared ascent with Russell I observing and following respectively, which went well - once 6m stops were done, thye descended quite quickly - Russell and I stayed with them, which caused some discomfort for my ears. We re-ascended and Lauren did her "mask off swim" skill at 6m, when we got up to about 5m I found myself light and it was awkward keeping bouyancy level - made sure my computer was happy I didn't need any more stop time and called it and came up rather than knacker myself given the awkward exit facing us to get out.
Came out and verified I handly lost any weights. Kit was exactly the same as previous week which hadn't had any such problems
All in all, a pretty unenjoyable dive.

dive.tags: 30M Assisted Ascent as Donor, MD7, Master Diver
dive.notes:
By the time of the second dive of the day tide had started coming in and visibility had improved a bit.
Took our bearings and swam out as a foursome to depth, came back in a little before doing shared ascent with Harvey with myself as donor on a swim in (rather than going straight up).
Managed the donor assist fairly comfortably and as we came in we found the reef by accident - very small and featureless.
For the whole five the only real life of interest were some young dogfish dotted around.

Day at St Catherine's pier with Gordon Laing, Russell Leith, Harvey Williamson, Donald Ralston, Kyle McArdle, Kerry Russell, Steve Very & George Martin. Also with the Mrtin & Laing families who were on a pyromaniacal mission most of the day,
Van shared with Steve Very on his first Scottish Dive trip and after hitting sleet on the Rest & Be Thankful arrived to find a glorious still sunny day at the Pier.
Did a quick dive brief, Gordon Harvey and DonaldR went off to do a 30m ascent and George and I buddied up for a fun dive with George as dive lead to practice dive leading and SMB.
Got ourselves out to the end of the pier, took a bearing and headed off towards a bouy and let George navigate out. Realised that George was going to run along at 12m - given it was low tide, I didn't want to have to stay at 11m on 2nd dive on a higher tide so go George to drop a bit lower (wrist slate is really useful!)
Had a nice bimble along - loads of norway lobsters, loads of different crabs including quite a big crab lobster and loads of large starfish.
Couple of times we crept a bit deep briefly when caught out by the terrain.
George kept a good watch on myself, checking air well, kept me in in reasonable range and called the turnaround perfectly - only issue being he did and 180 then started taking us back along at same depth through our own kicked up silt - used slate again and we ascended to 14m or so.
Noted we passed a large chain just before the turnaround - didnt recalled that chain at this site and was briefly confused that I was getting muddled with the slates.
As we passed the half hour mark, George started taking us gently up the bank and apart from a small detour to inspect an old wheel that had some life.
Just as I began to think about the SMB ascent, I clocked that George's SMB reel had been letting out and he had a long trail of string behind him. Given how cold it was and late in the dive we were, i didnt see anything to be gained by messing about getting the reel sorted, so used the slate again to indicate no SMB skill - George understood and took us up perfectly gdoing both 6m and 3m safety spots, bringing us out just a tiny bit short of the pier - very well done given the lack of landmarks at St Cats to navigate by at that point.
Only small critiscm was could have both watched our depth better to stay on the right side of the 15.
Kit - 14 Kg weight hardness - 2x 2Kg black trim weights in BCD - Thermals - PBB Undersuit - Cressi BCD - Otter Drysuit - 15L cylinder Weighted well

2nd dive of the day.
Followed same plan as first dive, but left from other side of pier as tide higher.
Again, George did well just bumping below the desired 14m now and again. Stops done we did SMB ascent. anaged a bit of 3m stop before George lost his bouyancy and surfaced. My profile shows me holding back to see if he was coming back down, then going up to avoid losing contact.
Turned out we'd come in rather short, current running different way slightly perhaps, so a good stretch of the leg to fin in.

Fun trip to A frames with Alan Bews, Harvey Williamson and Pamela Morley.
Very standard dive over the now very familar A Frames

Weather: Sunny slightly overcast, stiff breeze Sea: Choppy / surf at shore Visibility: 20m Temp: 14?
Holiday to Malta staying at the San Antonio Hotel, St Pauls Bay, Malta, just the 4 of us. Cool and a bit wet for Malta overall. Booked a holiday dive myself with Maltaqua - bit of trek from the hotel,but very highly recommended. Well looked after at reception and the staff were really good checking backgrounds, checked my PADI certs online and went through my log book.
For the dive itself, I joined up with a group of BSAC divers from south east england who were all there together on holiday diving all week. I was paired with Danny who had just joined Maltaqua for the forthcoming season. We made our way up to Cikewwa in strange somewhat rough & ready custom vans - A mixture of an Australian Ute, a bus and Navids van. Danny & I got ourselves ready - Danny in a familar looking otter drysuit and me in the usual bobbly hired wetsuit and looked around to find our english compatriots just starting to consider building some kit, so we dekitted a little and relaxed, Danny commenting you can tell what divers only dive on holiday and those that are used to diving in icy conditions!
The dive itself was a big step off the harbour wall, being wary of getting smashed back into the wall in the surf, pair up and swim out just under surface to preserve air and starting to drop down once the Boltenhagen cam into view - only about 150m from the shore.
Plenty of life and plenty to explore on the boat, only having been scuttled there in 2007.
Back in was mirror of trip out, but came up a rocky beach rather than try and negotiate hardour steps in the swell.

Second dive of the day, very similar type of dive to the P29, but the tug itself has been sunken a lot longer and is a sturdier, less impressive boat but loads of wildlife, much was which was very playful.
Stopped off for a beer on the way back, where one of the senior dive masters asked a few questions about how I got on with Danny - suspect Danny is still on probation, but he'd been brilliant with me - lots of "trust but verify", e.g. he asked if I had done wall jumps, but also asked how many, when last one was and askedwhat you should always remember to do before jumping, so couldnt fault him.

Club group trip to Farne Islands.
Drove down with Steve VEry and met up with rest of club (Donald, Russell, Kerry, Kyle, AlanB) as well as Thomas and Vince.
Not a great start to the day - had to cart all kit about half a mile from roadside to the very end of the harbour - sweaty and tied before getting on what turned out to be a very packed boat with 30+ divers on it.
Buddied up with Vince and had an amazing dive and saw loads of seals playing.

After a nice trip round the puffins had a second dive.
More of a gully dive this time, with seals being harder to spot as they were above and below hidden in amongst lots of broad leafed kelp but still good fun.
Surfaced on Vinces SMB, wondered why Vince jumped on my back - turned out to be a seal playing.
After a 35 minute wait on the surface wondering which of the 3 identical boats in the are was ours, we were picked up and made our way back to harbour.
At harbour, I managed to ping my dive computer off into the grey murky waters of the harbour.
Got a phone call later in teh week to say it was found but it was never returned.

Kimberleys first dive since last October, first with Lanzarote Dive Centre who picked us up and took us to Play Chica.
Saw a lovely little seahorse holding onto a bitof rope and a stingray hiding in the sand.
Lovely relaxed dive with no isues

Second dive of the day, as before, beach entry from Playa Chica.
Agreed with Val to buddy with Kimberley allowing Val to supervise the other lone diver more closely who had struggled with bouyancy. We agreed and made our way out and through the blue hole.
Another great dive, no issues.

Alothough listed as Playa Chica, this was actually a boat dive and further out from shore than usual as a result.
Great dive although Kimberley was struggling with her mask constantly flooding. She also said afterwards she was also worried about how much air she was going through.
Saw trumpet fish, kermit crabs and shoals of the silvery bream-like fish.

2nd boat dive of the day and another chance to explore the wrecks just off the old harbour all.
Again, trumpet fish, tuna and stingrays to be seen.

Dive to The Cathedral with Valerie from LDC and Andy
Walked out to Play Chica beach, swam out to mouth of the bay the dropped down and swam out to reef and out the cathedral. Sadly, camera refused to switch on.
On way out a young manta ray swam across our path.
Cathedral itself was very colourful with some beautiful yellow corals growing but not much life.
Saw much more on return dive round the craggy wall, with some decent sized gruppers going about.
Narrowly avoided going into deco on return, having crept back down to 27m

Second dive of the day with Valerie and Andy
Kimberley sat the dive out as not feeling 100% after the first dive so we dived as 3.
Plan was to head in roughly the same area as Cathedral, but to head further out to try and see some bigger wildlife (rays gruppers etc).
Took big stride off side of Playa Chica pier with Andy, swam out to the dive ring and descended and headed off approx 210 degrees.
Lovely swim round a stepped ledge spotting some beautiful life, lots of corals, the odd sea slug and a couple of nudibranches. Learned to spot what are shark beds.
At about 13 minute mark, a large Ray came into view and it slowly swam past right past field of view, about 15 metres below us - definitely the highlight of the trip.
The distraction however caused me to take my eye off my depth, dropping to 34m and I think also getting narc'd and stopped watching my NDL time and went just into deco.
We rose up to about 26m and continued the dive, seeing some lovely reasonably big gruppers and a also a large-ish seahorse.
We continued up to 6 meters - Valeries computer showed us clear, Andy's computer was requiring a descent back to 25m, where as mine was requiring an 11 minute stop at 6 meters with a warning not to go above 3m. We didn't have sufficient air to descend, but we did have enough to carry out the safety stop required by my computer, so I beached myself on a clear Sandy area and conserved air as best I could, which worked as I managed to surface with 60 bar remaining,

Weather: Sunny & Cold Sea: Flat Calm Tide: Flood Visibility: 3-5metres Temp: 8 Mix: Air
Fun dive with Cammy who was a recent PADI crossover. Was asked to keep an eye on his bouyancy and how observant he was of his buddy for feedback. It was a very enjoyable dive - cammy was very calm and sedate. I did find it hard work and difficult to observe cammy closely as he's a "fin follower" and followed directly behind me, plus he didn't have a torch so I let in a fair bit of water straining my neck round to keep an eye on him.
Kept everything nice and conservative and got cammy back to the surface on 80 bar.

Weather: Sunny Sea: Flat Calm Tide: High Visibility: 3-4 metres Temp: 8 Mix: Air
Second dive with Cammy and it was a great calm little five.
We found a lobster nursery, saw a conger eel and a couple of pipe fish.
I overshot my navigation - I mistook the long beam for what would have been another beam behind us further east - realised when we heard the finnart oil tanker engine getting close. Turned and headed back, and did weight check with cammy at 3 to 4 metres in the sand and managed to take 2kg off him before he started to lift, so he should be well set up for his next dive.

Weather: Dry & Still Sea: Calm Tide: Low
First dive after lockdown: Diving n a 3 with Donald and Terry practicing dive lead for practice as he does is his PADI AOW crossover.
My bouyancy was surpisingly well controlled given how long I had been out the water but was not perfect and my lack of practice was showing a little.
Lots of fish and little flatfish being curious as we descended down the slope to the reef. We bimbled along the the reef having a good nose around, very pleasant. After a time, Terrys mask completely flooded - he got it cleared and settled again but indicated he'd had enough so we made our safety stops and got to shore.

Weather: Fair Sea: Calm Tide: Flood
2nd dive of day, this time with Alice
Alice had problems with ears on way down but cleared after a couple of pauses and slight ascends and we lowly got down to the reef. Spotted one Conger lurking and a big lobster on the reef.
We were to locate and recover Russell's buoy so we shortened the dive slightly and couldn't zigzag up the roof too much.
Had some fun taking my time making sure we didn't tangle the buoy with a small anchored boat that was beng swung around a fair bit in the wind.

Fun dive with Gayle who had recently completed PADI AOW crossover. Odd dive - very poor vis, maybe a meter or two most of the time and it seemed like the way the tide was opening out after the restriction in the width of the loch at the caravan park was making for some strange currents under the water.
The tide appeared to be running west to east, so initial concern as we set out to head east to the wall was that we would get swept past it. On first attempt, we swam out to the bouy, took a heading and dropped to a 4 meters and began finning towards wall.
As it felt like we were swimming against the tide, combined with seeing a couple of divers from our group heading in the opposite diretion to ourselves, I indicated to surface and check bearings. Upon surfacing I found that we had actually been pulled in a westerly direction - we were right down the beach, so we came back to shore and walked back round to the entry point again and headed back out to the bouy & line.
We got ourselves settled , re-checked bearings and dripped back down the shot line, found a stick to stand up as a marker to try to mark track progress and headed off.
Visibility was awful for most of the dive but we managed to find the wall, where it cleared a little and we could enjoy the dive - spotted baby scallops, squat lobsters and a big lions mane jellyfish that we kept well clear of. As we explored the wall, Gayle lost her find - managed to retrieve it get it back on without any drama, but we did seem to have both gone through a fair bit of air, so we turned and made our way carefully headed back, wary of over overshooting the entry point and risking getting swirled back out into the middle of the loch, but despite getting confused by the currents again, we got it fairly spot on and came up just a little west of the bouy, having completed safet stops correctly.

Pretty much same as first dive of the day, only without the false starts and confusion from the tides. Vis still shocking but we still managed a far better exploration of the wall and enjoyed the swim back in.
Weather: Sunny Sea: Calm Visibility: 2 Temp: 13?

PADI DSD with Blair and Isla. Valerie had another pair of DSD divers to take out, so asked that I keep Blair and Isla as my buddies and supervise them to allow Valerie to manager the other pair far enough away to avoid collisions.
Kept my pair close, got them kitted and comfortable at the shallow and edged them in and we all dropped in the shallows at the same time. Blair was fine, but Isla turned out to be really under-weighted - gave her all the spare weight I could from my spares and Vals and managed to get her down, but with hindsight probably needed a little more to be heavier and better balanced.
Blair was perfectly comfortable, OIsla looked very nervous so stayed close. Val was struggling with her DSD,one of whome was having what looked like ear problems so I just kept us reasonably close but out of the way as we eased down the slope - Isla was stilla little bit floaty but as we got to beyond 4 meters it settled and just as I started to relax and work out how to get Blair to see more, I looked awy from Isla for a second and looked back to see her with no regulator - got her reg back in and clear no problem and tried to settle her but it was clear she was getting close to panic. I tried to get Val's attention to hand over Blair to her, but without success, so rather than risk losing anyone, with Isla on the brink of panic, I gathered the two of them together, got my arm through their BCDs so they were both secure and did an approximation of a resuce lift, using Bairs bigger BCD as lift. Managed a a token safety stop and surfaces the two of them and managed to get my own BCD inflated as I started to drop again.
Tried to catch Vals attention from the surface but this was fruitless, so rafted the 3 of is into the shore and dekitted. Blair loved it, Isla decided it wasn't for her. I felt bad the dive was cut short, but pleased no harm came to anyone and every handled calmly and safely.
DSD with Blair

Dive Organiser: Fiona Watson Dive Purpose: Day out wth Wreckspeditions - first club trip with Jason, meeting up at jetty at Loch Goil Cruisers. Dive risk & plan notes: Jason Coles was skipper and dive master Kit Setup: My standard set up - (Otter drysuit, NDiver Weightbelt, Cressi BCD, heavy o'three undersuit) and extra base layer as cold. Species Encountered: nill of note Activities Observed: nill of note Skills Completed or Practiced: n/a Kit Repair Notes: None General Notes: Met up with Jason at Roll-in from rhib with Donald, first in a long time, but was fun. Wall dive with Donald - pretty disappointing as lack of life on the wall. Donalds suit had flooded and at 30 minutes in he signalled cold and we ascended and donald put up SMB and got picked up by Jason almost immediately.
Great set up on boat, Jason runs the boat really well and Hot Choclate was top notch, just a shame the dive itself wasn't great - probbaly mostly down to time of year.

Dive Organiser: Fiona Watson Dive Purpose: Day out wth Wreckspeditions - first club dive with Jason Dive risk & plan notes: Jason Coles was skipper and dive master Kit Setup: My standard set up Species Encountered: nill of note Activities Observed: nill of note Skills Completed or Practiced: n/a Kit Repair Notes: None General Notes: Dive with Donald - dropped down shot line to the Avrella with Donald. Enjoyed a tour around the boat observing some nice life. Despite only being at ~25m, suspect I got a little narc'd as lost my bearings and got confused at the stern of the boat. completed the first circumnavigation and found the shot line again - I assumed we would have a look over the deck at shallower depth but Donald had decided that given he was cold, he didnt want to have to find the line again, so we just ascended.

Dive Organiser: Russel Leitch Dive Purpose: Training day for Julie & Arwen, Dive time for recently qualified Peter. Alan to observe Donald in with new diver. First dive after having Covid, Dive risk & plan notes: Standard A Frames notes regarding access. Kit Setup: My standard set up Species Encountered: nill of note Activities Observed: nill of note Skills Completed or Practiced: n/a Kit Repair Notes: None General Notes: Diving as a 3 observing Donald out with recently-qualified branch diver. Observed Peter having a little a bit of difficulty with bouyancy and generally not looking comfortable - signalled to Donald and got his spare dive torch out his pocket and clipped to Peter and got switched on for him and indicated he should use the torch - this immediately stopped Peter from overthinking everything and his bouyancy settled. Learnings: Covid definitely has affected diving slightly - lung capacity is definitely lower.

Second dive of the day, led the Dive with Peter, a recently qualified branch diver.
I set the the direction and navigated down and to the reef, but let Peter explore reefs at his pace. Had a couple of moments with Peters bouyancy early in the dive, but caught and prevented ascent (shown in the dive log just after got down to 14m) - pointed out some lobster and some very young pran or lobsters under a rock,
Swithered about extending diver for another sweep over the reef but was a little concerned Peter would get cold (I was starting to feel it a little also) so began ascent - we came up slowly and I had actually cleared my 6m safety stops on my computer when Peter lost control of bouyancy and began to ascend. Rather than try hard to to pull him down and risk freaking him out, I just slowed the ascent as best I could by holding his arm and dumping and came to surface - not ideal. We discussed at surface, Peter to adda little weight to cover emptying cylinder and a weight check to be done when appropriate (Peter is still finalising equipment and changing things so pointless fine tuining until he's settled).

Day's diving with Steve Very, Paul Cornwell, Alice Brodie and Alan Cooper.
As per dive plan, we all convened at Balloch McDonalds, checked the weather which was perfectly calm conditions and agreed to head to Conger Alley as per dive plan.
We ran as two pairs, Steve and Paul in first with myself and Alice on shore, then swapped.
This was my first "flexi" day taken from Exizent that allowed a fun dive with Steve Very, Paul Cornwell and Alice Brodie at Conger Alley.
Cold but mostly dry & sunny day.
Nice bimble across a familiar reef - no wildlife of any exceptional note - one lobster and usual array of crabs and small fish.
Did find a cylinder insert on a rock that it transpired had been left there by another club member the previous weekend

First "flexi" day taken from Exizent that allowed a fun dive with Steve Very, Paul Cornwell and Alice Brodie at Conger Alley.
Cold but mostly dry day.
Nice bimble across a familiar reef - no wildlife of any exceptional note - one lobster and usual array of crabs and small fish.

Day at Seal Reef to try and get some Master Diver skills signed off. Minor alteration to plans for other divers as Russell and Richard hadn't made it up.
Went in with James J and Alan B with intention of carrying out 30m shared Ascent. All began well, I was neutrally bouyant and comfortable, James gave good signals for training and then indicated out of air so my octopus was donated to James and we then attempted to carry out a swim in up the reef without touching reef. Got ourslf comfortable and in contact with one anothers shoulder straps to prevent seperation and began to try ascent - could not get James off the bottom, Tried normal approach of adding air and breathign in to start ascent, then a kick, then more kicks but no scent and was beginning to get disorientated and was drifting. After a while floundering it, signalled to abandon and swam in up the slope.
Agreed on surface to have a bimble over the reef with remaining air with a view to a good surface interval before another attempt.
Seal reef was unusually quiet with very few squat lobsters.
Alice and Steve reported seeing dolphins and seal while we were under.

Attempt two of the day to caryr out 30 shared ascent.
Suspecting I may have been overweighted on first attempt I did not add any weight when switching from 15l to 12l cylinder.
Followed same procedure as before, slightly better in that mamaged to get James off the bottom to about 4metres, but James lost air from neck seal and we ended up back on the deck.
Had a couple more attempts until I started to feel that my frustration was starting to lead to panic, and upon seeing I'd gone through 60bar of air, indicated strongly I'd had enough and was heading bak to shore,
Everything fine from here, started safety stop as normal, but from one minute in could feel myself becoming overly bouyant and a couple of breaths later I was unable to maintain neutral bouyancy and had an uncontrolled ascent from about 5 meters.
Can safely say I was not over-weighted on either dive - explained this on surface and followed up with BDO and training lead recommending to do a proper 3m weight check on James on the next appropriate shore dive.

Diving from MV Oceanic.
Neep tides going out to hit low tide slack water.
Lovely if overcast mornign with a slight well but no chopiness on the water.
My first time diving with Terry and Terry's first drysuit boat dive after crossing over from PADI. Felt a bit off before going in attributed to a touch of sea sickness.
Leaguers Buss was very scenic, practically carpeted with of anemonies, dead mans fingers and <brocolli shaped things to be researched>
Very little in the way of animal life which was a little disappointing but a generally good dive helping to build hours up again.
Bit of fast ascent before and after 6m stop, but not uncontrolled, bouyancy not brilliant holding a steady depth for 3 minute 6m safety stop - unsure if this contrbuted towards not feelng great when surfacing - ear pain and headache on surface so sat out second dive as precaution and all passed after an hour or so.

Quick dive to complete shared ascent (recipient) with Russell as donor and Alan Bews observing.
Early on visibility looked like it was going to be terrible but was just a band of horrible possibly pollen-filed water.
Swam out and dropped and managed to find a spot with enough depth to record.
Straight down, indicated exercise, I then indicated out of air and went onto Russells octopus.
Came up with Russell nice and easy, gentle kick up when neededgot us lifting and was nice and controlled from there.

Fun dive after shared assist - shored dive from twin piers - out and to the reef on left as usual.
Loads of life - sea floor covered in anemonies and coral and loads and loads of tiny jelly fish going about.
Passed 4 Congers on the reef.
Really nice relaxed dive - probably the best and most comfortable I've felt underwater since before lockdown

Skills dive followed by bimble.
Swam out and dropped to 10m and found a sandy area behind the pierto carry out BCD off skill.
Got BCD off no problem, arranged equipment tidily and managed swim around without difficulty (though a very slightly longer reg hose might be useful in future)
after swim about dropped the BCD back onto the seabed, checked all straps, arranged reg hose and manouvred right arm in, and lay back onto the seabed on the BCD and managed to get arm in, but while doing this managed to pull the exterior weight pouch clip off the side of the BCD.
Took my time and managed to get all equipmen on reasonably tidy, flipped onto knees and got BCD tidied and tightened all straps and set off for a bimble along the reef.
Again loads of life, even more congers including one that was absolutely huge (could only see head but the jaw alone had to be 8 inches) - eft him well alone.

Dougie Turnbull Driving in big van on a wet, miserable and slightly windy June saturday morning. Plan for today was originally for Finnart. Changed to Seal Reef on the morning as weather forecast made us think the steady wind would be driving over the loch onto the shore at Finnart. Looked "OK" as we passed but we headed to St Catherines anyway, where it was far too choppy to attempt - headed back to Arrochar looking to try other Long Long sites, but ended up back at Finnart - Peter & Julie Kennedy decided agianst diving in the weather, myself, Dougie, Alan B and Alice agreed to press on as win was dropping.
Previous day had seen really heavy downpours and this was reflected in the viz, which at points was terrible.
Fun dive with Alice, dropped down to 26m and dound the piers, did a single, slow scan over the piers, saw some decent sized scallops, a few corkwing wrasse. Alice also almost leant on a grey gurnard that had been minding his own business on the seabed.
Viz was terrible and did briefly lose Alice at about 7m - did standard seperation procedure and began turning flashing torch, concentrating on where I thought I'd last seen her - spotted her torch as she did the same from about 3-4 metres away from me!
Towards the end of the dive found a lovely little butterfih and spent a couple of minutes watching it hiding itself in a crack on some concrete.
Alice had been indicating something up with her suit inflator - turns out she had a leak so she didn't want to spend any longer so we came up after first pass over the piers - Alice then decided against a second dive as she was cold and wet.

Second dive of the day - As Alice had gotten wet on previous dive, we were down to three - Alan B was keen to get Dougie in for his 6th dive so he can get his BD qualification and wanted me to take on as instructor with Alan supervising us both.
Given conditions - everyone was feeling wet, cold and miserable, we agreed a quick 30 minute dive - poor viz and a really high tide meant we were unlikely to see much of interest.
Sorted out an early issue with Dougie who had somehow managed to get his torch wrapped around his primary hose.
After that, gently dropped down to 14ish meters and managed to find the tip of the long concrete section, so we spent the dive exploring up and down that - found a small adult lobster, another, bigger butterfish and usual crabs, spotted a couple of small cod hanging around us.
Good learning experience - never realised how hard it is to make progress and keep bouyancy when having to look behind to keep trainee (who wants to fall back and follow) close - very wet neck and found myself fingertipping along the bottom.
Also discovered that signalling the lobster sign can be misinterpreted as "go grab that lobster"!
Couple of brief moments on way back in about 5m when I thought Dougie might be getting a little bit floaty and maybe at risk of getting away from me so just gave him a genttle pull down. Other than that, no issues or incidents.
